The latter of the children which houses the "sign in" button has the property justify-content: flex-end
Does the flex not span the whole width? or does it only as long as the contents in it?

Adding justify-content to an element will only cause its children to be positioned along that axis. It won't position the element itself along its parent axis.

So by giving the sign in button a display of flex and/or justify-content of flex-end, will only cause its children to be positioned at flex-end. It won't cause it to be placed at the flex-end of the navbar container.

Have you tried giving the navbar container a justify-content property?
I used justify-content in those two classes, but not the parent element of both that uses .navbar

One way to see what's going on would be using the dev tools, and using the element selector tool (should look like an arrow icon in the upper left of the dev tools). You'll be able to see the width of each element when you hover over it, or you can hover over the element in the HTML of the dev tools.

Trying to add a justify-content property to the main navbar element is one way you could go about it, though you would want to look into the different values you can use for it.

You could also edit the child navbar elements as well to make it work the way you intended, which after you take a peak at them in dev tools you might get some ideas on what to toy around with.
